SUMMARIZER="J">

President Corazon Aquino today reversed a long-held policy and said she was willing to 
negotiate cease-fires with Communist guerrillas and former soldiers who have staged 
coup attempts. Mrs. Aquino also invited her most outspoken critic Sen. Juan Enrile to 
join the talks. Enrile said he was willing to reconcile with Mrs. Aquino, who fired him as 
defense minister after he was implicated in a coup attempt in November 1986. 

No one has claimed responsibility for the explosions that occur almost daily in Manila. 
The Government blames them on Communist rebels who have repeatedly tried to topple 
Aquino.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d090"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA101390-0087"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="J">

President Aquino used small bombers and artillery to end a rebellion led by renegade 
army Col. Alexander Noble on Mindanao, countering charges that her government is 
indecisive. The Oct. 4-6 uprising never spread to the military underground on other 
islands.

Aquino has survived two major coup attempts and several aborted military mutinies. 
Most ended in standoffs or dragged on for days because military leaders were reluctant to 
order troops to fire on other soldiers.

Noble's rebellion coincided with the release of a government report that concluded coup 
attempts will probably continue -- but unlikely to succeed -- for the indefinite future.</SUM>
